@PedsPro, I'd also like to add that it's important to remember that children can't always communicate how they're feeling, so it's up to us as caregivers to be extra observant. 
For example, if your child is experiencing abdominal pain, they might not be able to tell you where it hurts or how severe it is. However, you might notice that they're not eating as much as usual or that they're crying more than usual. 
By paying attention to these subtle cues, you can help ensure that your child gets the care they need, even if they can't communicate exactly what's wrong.
